<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Due to its rare status and sporadic nature 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. (G.) campestris" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="campestris" subGenus="G.">G. (G.) campestris</taxonomicName>
is included in the red lists 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10531-006-9123-9" author="Hochkirch, A" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Conservation" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="3597 - 3607" refId="B11" refString="Hochkirch, A, Witzenberger, KA, Teerling, A, Niemeyer, F, 2007. Translocation of an endangered insect species, the field cricket (Gryllus campestris Linnaeus 1758) in northern Germany. Biodiversity Conservation 12: 3597 - 3607, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10531-006-9123-9" title="Translocation of an endangered insect species, the field cricket (Gryllus campestris Linnaeus 1758) in northern Germany." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10531-006-9123-9" volume="12" year="2007">Hochkirch et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. It is flightless in its habitat of dune, short grasses, chalky soil, and light sandy porous soils. During our field survey we collected material from different districts. Our examination demonstrates that this species has morphological similarity to 
<taxonomicName genus="G." lsidName="G. (Gryllus) bimaculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="bimaculatus" subGenus="Gryllus">G. (Gryllus) bimaculatus</taxonomicName>
but few differences in wing pattern and head morphology identifies each species.
</paragraph>
